AGI - "I also think about what will be after me, I'll talk about it first." Pope Francis spoke of his successor in one of the two interviews issued to the director of the Tg1, Gian Marco Chiocci>, now published in the book "Dialogo con Papa Francesco - Don't Fear of Death", > these days in the library for Compagnia Editoriale Aliberti.&nbsp;And just in the moments when the cardinals are closed in <a href="https://www.si.it/estero/new
"There is always &nbsp; that melancholy of the past: a &nbsp; what happens in institutions, e&nbsp;also in the Church. There are those &nbsp; who want to go back:> gli&nbsp;indietristi, who do not accept that&nbsp; the Church goes ahead, that is in&nbsp;cammino. It is always on the way, &nbsp; the Church must grow. Also&nbsp; his way of being a Church must grow, from the roots, with the tre&nbsp;princìpi so beautiful of Vincenzo di&nbsp;Lérins, the father of the fifth century: ut annis&nbsp;consolidetur, dilatetur tempore, sublimetur aetate. From the roots, like the juice of the tree that grows and rises,&nbsp; but always attached to the root.&nbsp;A Church that breaks from the roots &nbsp; goes back, and loses this juicy &nbsp; of healthy tradition. That is not&nbsp;conservativeism: tradition grows and must go on." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<br> Chiocci, the first to bring a Pope to Tg1>, reports the texts of the two interviews with Bergoglio: that of 2020 in full pandemic and the second, 45 minutes aired on Rai1 on November 1, 2023 a few weeks from the beginning of the war in the Middle East. And just from the October 7 attack the interview begins. "War is a defeat. I felt an extra defeat. They are two people who must live together, with that wise solution: Two states, well defined, and Jerusalem with a special status" > is the first reflection that Bergoglio entrusts to the journalist with the thought also to another people at war, the Ukrainian one to which until the end he addressed a thought and a prayer. "The Ukrainian is a martyr people.> We do not forget that he suffered very strong persecutions at the time of Stalin".&nbsp;And yet "the second day of the war in Ukraine, I went to the Russian embassy. I heard I had to go. - he told Pope Francis - To the ambassador I said I was willing to go to Putin>, if it needed anything. The ambassador was good – now he finished his post, became an official in Russia. From that moment I had a good interview with the Russian embassy" and "Lavrov wrote to me: thanks for the offer &nbsp; to come to Moscow, but it is not necessary.&nbsp; Yes, I wanted to go to both sides".
&nbsp;<br> But among the pages that make the Synod's budget, they address the need for renewal of the Church and the role of women in Catholicism > words emerge that describe well what was outlined in his 13 years in St. Peter. The attention for migrants, to whom he dedicated one of his first apostolic visits to Lampedusa, throwing at sea a crown of flowers for all the victims of the Mediterranean.&nbsp; There are references to the greats of football – Maradona, Pelé and Messi – who return the most human and passionate face of Francis.
But "Dialogo con Papa Francesco" is not only political and religious analysis: the reader is also accompanied in the most intimate sphere of the Pontiff. A migrant who has not forgotten his origins deeply planted in Italy.» "I am the son of migrants. In Argentina we are forty-six million, I think, and indigenous people are only six million, not more, the others are all migrants. It is a country of migration: Italian, Spanish, Ukrainian, Russian, from the Middle East. All these who come from the Middle East we call them Turks, because they arrived with the Turkish passport of the great Ottoman Empire. I'm used to living in a migrant country. My dad worked at the Bank of Italy and went migrant in Argentina. He stayed there and died there. He put up a family there. For me the experience of migration is an existential thing, > strong. There were bad migrations even after the war; but today it is always a very dramatic thing".<br> A plause, the Pontiff, reserved it to the Ue>: "I liked it when the President of the European Parliament went to Lampedusa to see in person. I like this because it shows that the European Union is thinking of taking charge of the matter."
<br> In addition to reflections on migration and climate emergency, the book expresses Pope Francis' ability to speak to people's hearts, giving hope and tracing alternative paths to fear and hatred. After the resignation of Ratzinger,» Francis found himself living with an emeritus Pope, inheriting "a box" of documents representing &nbsp; cleaning work within the Church "to finish". &nbsp;&nbsp;It was precisely to Benedict XVI, the pope who died on 21 April, dedicated affectionate words: "I have done nothing but collect the witness of Pope Benedict, I have continued his work" and "Blessed for me is a father and a brother (...)&nbsp;&nbsp;He is a good man, is holiness made person".&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
And on how the Church is perceived among ordinary people, the Argentine pastor reports an anecdote. When Pope&nbsp died; John Paul II, "I was on a bus", recalls Francis, "stavo&nbsp; going to a favela>, when I was reached by the news that was&nbsp; making the world tour. During the Mass, I asked to pray for the deceased Father. After the celebration &nbsp; a poor woman approached me,» she asked about how the Pope was elected, I told her about the white smoke, the cardinals, the conclave. To which she interrupted me and said: “Senta Bergoglio, when he becomes Pope first remember to buy a dog”. I told her I would hardly become, and if in case I should have taken the dog... “Because every time he finds himself eating,” was his answer, “give a little bit before him, if he is well then continue to eat.” It was an exaggeration "but he realized the idea that the people of God, the poor among the poorest in the world, had of the House of the Lord crossed by deep wounds, intestine struggles and malversations". >
A pontificate marked by conflicts, by the pandemic that stopped the world > and that saw it only pray in St. Peter's Square, or go to the Church of St. Marcellin at the Course in a deserted Rome. Indelible images that will remain carved in the history of Rome and the world. But how can we not even remember the commitment to the environment? And to do so usually use a simple example taken by everyday ministry: "I like to talk about the fishermen of San Benedetto del Tronto: Good guys, who came to see me, and told me I don't know how many tons of plastic they fish. And they don't throw them back to the sea, they take them away, they lose money, but they take them away to clean the sea a little bit. We have behaved badly with the custody of Creation" and "We are still in time to stop: it is our future, it is the future of our children, our grandchildren. It takes some responsibility." &nbsp;
And in the end a note from typhous >: Maradona, Messi and "Pelé: these are the three players I followed. Maradona, as a big player. A big one. But as a man he failed. Poor guy, he slipped. With that court around those who praised him and didn't help him. He came to see me here the first year of pontificate. And then, poor man, he ended up... It's curious: so many sportsmen end badly. Even boxers. Lots of them end badly. That's curious. Messi is very correct. Correct. He's a gentleman. But for me, of these three, the great lord is Pelé.> He was a man of a heart... I spoke to Pelé, once I met him on a plane in Buenos Aires and talked to him... He was a man of such a great humanity... The three are great, each with its specialty. Messi is good right now. And Pelé was good."
&nbsp;
